{"cells":[{"cell_type":"code","source":["from google.colab import drive\n","drive.mount('/content/drive')"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"Z7J1MedLWTCE","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1781193038347,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":1376,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"56ac546f-4f49-4d30-bcf6-5979151a37fa"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["Drive already mounted at /content/drive; to attempt to forcibly remount, call drive.mount(\"/content/drive\", force_remount=True).\n"]}]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["%cd /content/drive/MyDrive/Repos/datasets"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"s3Scu7sCWVAN","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1781193038361,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":12,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"d2a6ece4-87a4-4fd5-f856-c1c1f10503a9"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["/content/drive/MyDrive/Repos/datasets\n"]}]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["# !pip install pyprind"],"metadata":{"id":"bE8VtMS9X4Bv"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["### **1. Introduction to Out-of-Core Learning**\n","\n","Grid searching and constructing feature vectors for massive datasets (like 50,000+ movie reviews) can easily exceed a standard computer's memory. To solve this, **out-of-core learning** is used. This technique allows you to work with massive datasets by fitting the classifier incrementally on smaller batches (mini-batches) of data using the Stochastic Gradient Descent optimization algorithm.\n","\n","### **2. Setting up the Data Stream and Tokenizer**\n","\n","To handle the data batch by batch, we first need to define a tokenizer function to clean the text, a generator function to stream the documents one by one from our local drive, and a function to grab specific mini-batches."],"metadata":{"id":"lvetF41tUXH4"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["\n","import numpy as np\n","import re\n","import nltk\n","from nltk.corpus import stopwords\n","\n","nltk.download('stopwords')\n","\n","stop = stopwords.words('english')\n","\n","def tokenizer(text):\n","    # Clean HTML tags\n","    text = re.sub('<[^>]*>', '', text)\n","    # Extract emoticons\n","    emoticons = re.findall(r'(?::|;|=)(?:-)?(?:\\)|\\(|D|P)', text)\n","    # Remove non-word characters, convert to lowercase, and append emoticons\n","    text = re.sub(r'[\\W]+', ' ', text.lower()) + ' '.join(emoticons).replace('-', '')\n","    # Tokenize and remove stop words\n","    tokenized = [w for w in text.split() if w not in stop]\n","    return tokenized\n","\n","def stream_docs(path):\n","    \"\"\"Generator function to read one document at a time.\"\"\"\n","    with open(path, 'r', encoding='utf-8') as csv:\n","        next(csv) # skip header\n","        for line in csv:\n","            text, label = line[:-3], int(line[-2])\n","            yield text, label\n","\n","def get_minibatch(doc_stream, size):\n","    \"\"\"Takes a document stream and returns a specific number of documents.\"\"\"\n","    docs, y = [], []\n","    try:\n","        for _ in range(size):\n","            text, label = next(doc_stream)\n","            docs.append(text)\n","            y.append(label)\n","    except StopIteration:\n","        return None, None\n","    return docs, y"],"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stderr","text":["[nltk_data] Downloading package stopwords to /root/nltk_data...\n","[nltk_data]   Package stopwords is already up-to-date!\n"]}],"execution_count":null,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"w2MxN72bUXH5","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1781193038375,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":11,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"b648e192-fb75-4b75-a0c2-59f213a1dc89"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["# Read in the first document\n","next(stream_docs(path='movie_data.csv'))"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"8Gx4vucWWCVn","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1781193038424,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":42,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"8b5c4e23-bb04-4709-c537-2736a872aa3c"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"execute_result","data":{"text/plain":["('\"In 1974, the teenager Martha Moxley (Maggie Grace) moves to the high-class area of Belle Haven, Greenwich, Connecticut. On the Mischief Night, eve of Halloween, she was murdered in the backyard of her house and her murder remained unsolved. Twenty-two years later, the writer Mark Fuhrman (Christopher Meloni), who is a former LA detective that has fallen in disgrace for perjury in O.J. Simpson trial and moved to Idaho, decides to investigate the case with his partner Stephen Weeks (Andrew Mitchell) with the purpose of writing a book. The locals squirm and do not welcome them, but with the support of the retired detective Steve Carroll (Robert Forster) that was in charge of the investigation in the 70\\'s, they discover the criminal and a net of power and money to cover the murder.<br /><br />\"\"Murder in Greenwich\"\" is a good TV movie, with the true story of a murder of a fifteen years old girl that was committed by a wealthy teenager whose mother was a Kennedy. The powerful and rich family used their influence to cover the murder for more than twenty years. However, a snoopy detective and convicted perjurer in disgrace was able to disclose how the hideous crime was committed. The screenplay shows the investigation of Mark and the last days of Martha in parallel, but there is a lack of the emotion in the dramatization. My vote is seven.<br /><br />Title (Brazil): Not Available\"',\n"," 1)"]},"metadata":{},"execution_count":19}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["---\n","\n","### **3. HashingVectorizer and Incremental Training**\n","\n","Standard vectorizers (`CountVectorizer` and `TfidfVectorizer`) cannot be used for out-of-core learning because they require holding the entire vocabulary in memory.\n","\n","Instead, we use **`HashingVectorizer`**, which is data-independent. It utilizes the \"hashing trick\" via the 32-bit MurmurHash3 function. By setting a large number of features, we reduce the chance of hash collisions. We then train an **`SGDClassifier`** (Stochastic Gradient Descent) with a logarithmic loss function (`loss='log'`), which effectively makes it a logistic regression classifier capable of incremental updates via the `partial_fit` method."],"metadata":{"id":"apzVv05fUXH6"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import HashingVectorizer\n","from sklearn.linear_model import SGDClassifier\n","import pyprind\n","\n","# Initialize HashingVectorizer\n","vect = HashingVectorizer(decode_error='ignore',\n","                         n_features=2**21,\n","                         preprocessor=None,\n","                         tokenizer=tokenizer)\n","\n","# Initialize SGDClassifier\n","clf = SGDClassifier(loss='log_loss', random_state=1)\n","doc_stream = stream_docs(path='movie_data.csv')\n","\n","# Setup progress bar and classes\n","pbar = pyprind.ProgBar(45)\n","classes = np.array([0, 1])\n","\n","# Iterate over 45 mini-batches of 1,000 documents each\n","for _ in range(45):\n","    X_train, y_train = get_minibatch(doc_stream, size=1000)\n","    if not X_train:\n","        break\n","    X_train = vect.transform(X_train)\n","    clf.partial_fit(X_train, y_train, classes=classes)\n","    pbar.update()"],"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stderr","text":["0% [##############################] 100% | ETA: 00:00:00\n","Total time elapsed: 00:00:35\n"]}],"execution_count":null,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"cHZjrf9lUXH6","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1781193074449,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":36027,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"b980abe4-b037-4647-fa94-14d7a53e73c1"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["---\n","\n","### **4. Model Evaluation**\n","\n","After the incremental learning process finishes (which is highly memory efficient and typically takes less than a minute), we evaluate the model using the remaining 5,000 documents in the dataset."],"metadata":{"id":"w6nKnEZJUXH6"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["# Fetch the last 5000 documents for testing\n","X_test, y_test = get_minibatch(doc_stream, size=5000)\n","X_test = vect.transform(X_test)\n","\n","# Print out the accuracy\n","print(f'Accuracy: {clf.score(X_test, y_test):.3f}')\n","\n","# Update the model with the test data\n","clf = clf.partial_fit(X_test, y_test)"],"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["Accuracy: 0.868\n"]}],"execution_count":null,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"2FGJH8_RUXH6","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1781193079133,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":4686,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"de1f7889-14bb-4bec-a0c1-2cc14d46b1eb"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["*(The expected accuracy is approximately 87%, slightly below the grid search method, but achieved with a fraction of the computational overhead).*\n","\n","---\n","\n","### **5. Note on Advanced Alternatives: Word2Vec**\n","\n","The document concludes by noting **word2vec** as a modern alternative to the bag-of-words model. Released by Google in 2013, word2vec is an unsupervised learning algorithm based on neural networks. It automatically learns relationships between words by clustering those with similar meanings into similar spaces. Its vector spacing allows for complex mathematical relationship reproduction, famously demonstrated by the equation:\n","\n","*king - man + woman = queen*"],"metadata":{"id":"QDjriDfHUXH6"}}],"metadata":{"colab":{"provenance":[]},"kernelspec":{"display_name":"Python 3","name":"python3"}},"nbformat":4,"nbformat_minor":0}